        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Herman Miller Aeron</strong> is the benchmark office chair, but at $1,395 it costs three times the Titan Evo. The Aeron has a mesh seat that breathes in summer, a 12-year warranty, and the PostureFit SL lumbar — but it does not recline past 125 degrees and has no head pillow. If budget is no object and you work in a warm climate, the Aeron is the better chair. See our <a href="/reviews/herman-miller-aeron-review/">Aeron review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Steelcase Gesture</strong> has the best armrests of any chair we have tested — they rotate 360 degrees and adjust in every direction — but at $979 it is more than double the Titan Evo. The Gesture's live lumbar is gentler than the Titan's L-Adapt, which some users prefer. If you want a premium office chair without the aggressive gaming-chair lumbar, the Gesture is the pick — see our <a href="/reviews/steelcase-gesture-review/">Gesture review</a> for details.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Branch Ergonomic Chair</strong> is the value champion at $349. It has an adjustable lumbar pad, a mesh back, and a 5-year warranty. The lumbar is a fixed pad, not adaptive, and the seat foam is softer and will sag faster than the Titan's cold-cure foam. If you want to save $100 and do not need the deep recline or magnetic pillow, the Branch is a solid choice — see our <a href="/reviews/branch-ergonomic-chair-review/">Branch review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Titan Evo 2022 if you game or work 6+ hours a day and want a chair that will not sag within a year. The cold-cure foam, adaptive lumbar, and 5-year warranty make it the best value in the mid-premium category. Choose the SoftWeave Plus fabric over PU leather for breathability and longevity.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Secretlab runs promotions around Prime Day, Black Friday, and its own anniversary sale where the Titan Evo drops to $399 or includes a free accessory bundle (head pillow, lumbar cushion, or armrest sleeves). We have seen it as low as $379 during clearance events. The chair is rarely out of stock, so patience pays.</p>

      <p>Skip the Titan Evo and buy the Branch Ergonomic Chair if you want to save $100 and do not need the deep recline or magnetic pillow. The Branch has a mesh back that breathes better in summer and an adjustable lumbar pad that is gentler. The trade-off is softer foam that will sag faster and a 120-degree recline.</p>

      <p>Consider the Herman Miller Aeron if you work in a warm climate and want a mesh seat that never warms up. The Aeron costs $946 more, but it breathes better, has a 12-year warranty, and holds its value on the used market. The trade-off is no head pillow, a 125-degree recline, and a firmer mesh seat that some users find uncomfortable.</p>

      <p>Buy a chair mat if you have soft flooring. The Titan Evo weighs 70+ lbs and will dent carpet and scratch hardwood over time. A $40 polycarbonate chair mat is the cheapest protection. Pair the chair with a <a href="/reviews/best-foot-rest-desk/">foot rest</a> if you are under 5'7" — the seat depth is generous, and a foot rest fixes the dangling-legs issue.</p>

